><h2>Participant Spotlight</h2><h3>Dominique Estival, </h3>=0A<img class=3D=
"participantpic" src=3D"http://www.hcsnet.edu.au/files2/pictures/picture-37=
.jpg" />=0A<h4>Research area: Natural Language Processing - Linguistics</h4=
>=0A<p><p>My research interests have included the investigation of the=20
computational modelling of language change, machine translation, grammar=20
formalisms, grammar development and linguistic engineering, and spoken=20
dialogue systems.  After receiving a PhD in linguistics from the University
of Pennsylvania, I became a computational linguist in=20
industry, first in a machine translation company and then at Wang=20
Laboratories (USA), then as a researcher at ISSCO in Switzerland, before
taking the position of lecturer in Computational Linguistics at the
University of Melbourne. I joined Syrinx Speech Systems to head the Natural
Language Processing group and lead the R&D project to develop a natural
language telephone dialogue system. As a Senior Research Scientist at DSTO,
I continued work on spoken dialogue systems, in the context of multi-media
interaction, and on MT tools.  As Senior Manager (Projects and Research) at
Appen in Sydney, I oversaw the research in language processing and led the
projects on Text Attribution (TAT) and Data Stream Profiling (DSP).</p>



<p>Currently I am on the organising committee for the 1st Australian Comput=
ational and Linguistics Olympiad (OzCLO).  This HCSNet sponsored event is a=
 linguistics competition for high school students with a focus on computati=
onal thinking as it relates to solving linguistics problems. In addition to=
 the traditional linguistics problems, OzCLO endeavors to introduce student=
s to computational problem solving as it relates specifically to natural la=
nguage data.  For more information please visit the website:<a href=3D"http=
://www.ozclo.org.au">http://www.ozclo.org.au</a>.</p>
</p>=0A<div class=3D"contact">=0A<b>Contact:</b><br>=0ADominique Estival<br=
>=0A<br>=0Aemail: <a href=3D"mailto:estival@ozemail.com.au">estival@ozemail=
.com.au</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;www: <a href=3D"http://www.ics.mq.=
edu.au/~destival/">www.ics.mq.edu.au/~destival/</a><br>=0A</div>=0A</div>=
=0A<div style=3D"clear:both" /><div class=3D"news">=0A<a name=3D"news"></a>=
<h2>News</h2>=0A<h3>Call for Papers: Future Computer Applications for Manag=
ing Speech and Language Disorders Workshop</h3>



<p>Date: 19th September, 2008</p>



<p>Venue: State Library of Queensland (Brisbane, Queensland)</p>



<p>Contact: Dr David Copland (<a href=3D"mailto:d.copland@uq.edu.au <mailto=
:d.copland@uq.edu.au>">d.copland@uq.edu.au <mailto:d.copland@uq.edu.au></a>=
)</p>



<p>Description:</p>

<p>The ARC Human Communication Sciences Network (HCSNet) is holding a works=
hop that will focus on computer applications for assessing and treating spe=
ech, language, and communication disorders including current proven methods=
 and potential future applications from other fields (e.g. computer-based l=
anguage learning). New computer technologies may enable more intensive deli=
very of therapy than traditional modes and may address the need for quick, =
objective and reliable measures of speech and language function that are cl=
inically useful for assessment, diagnosis, and treatment monitoring. This w=
orkshop considers advances have been made in the development of computer-ba=
sed applications across a range of disciplines (e.g. virtual reality, speec=
h recognition) that may be utilised in the management of both developmental=
 and adult communication disorders. The workshop will provide a forum for i=
nteractions between a range of disciplines including speech pathology clini=
cians and researchers, computer scientists, linguistics, software developer=
s, engineers, speech scientists, occupational and rehabilitation therapists=
, and cognitive psychologists.</p>



<p>International keynote speakers include:</p>
<p>Professor Ron Cole (University of Colorado, USA) who has developed virtu=
al therapists for teaching and assessing reading in children and treating s=
peech and language production and comprehension in aphasia(<a href=3D"http:=
//cslr.colorado.edu/beginweb/vt_th/vt_th.html">http://cslr.colorado.edu/beg=
inweb/vt_th/vt_th.html</a>).</p>

<p>Professor Valerie Hazan (University College London) who has been researc=
hing auditory/visual computer-based perceptual training for language learni=
ng

(<a href=3D"http://www.phon.ucl.ac.uk/home/val/home.html">http://www.phon.u=
cl.ac.uk/home/val/home.html</a>).</p>



<p>Potential topics of interest include:</p>

<p>        Automated speech recognition

=C2=B7        Telerehabilitation

=C2=B7        Virtual therapy and teaching

=C2=B7        Automated text analysis

=C2=B7        Human-Computer Interactions

=C2=B7        Augmentative and alternative computer-based communication

=C2=B7        Computer-based speech, language, and reading treatment.

=C2=B7        Biofeedback

=C2=B7        Computerised discourse analysis

=C2=B7        Computer-based language learning applications.</p>



<p>Please submit a title and an abstract (up to 250 words) to David Copland=
 (<a href=3D"mailto:d.copland@uq.edu.au <mailto:d.copland@uq.edu.au>">d.cop=
land@uq.edu.au <mailto:d.copland@uq.edu.au></a>) by the 1st of August, 2008=
 indicating (1) if you are a student, (2) if you are a member of HCSNet, an=
d (3) if you wish to be considered for a travel bursary.  Further informati=
on can be found at (<a href=3D"http://www.hcsnet.edu.au/hcsnetevents/2008/h=
cdworkshop">http://www.hcsnet.edu.au/hcsnetevents/2008/hcdworkshop</a>)</p>
